context: Originally known as <a0_0><b8_0>Buckingham House<b8_0/><a0_0/>, the building at the core of today's palace was a large townhouse built for the <a1_0><a5_0><b9_0>Duke of Buckingham<b9_0/><a5_0/><a1_0/> in 1703 on a site that had been in private ownership for at least 150 years. It was acquired by <a2_0><b10_0>King George III<b10_0/><a2_0/> in 1761 as a private residence for Queen Charlotte and became known as <a3_0><b11_0>"The Queen's House"<b11_0/><a3_0/>. During the 19th century it was enlarged, principally by architects <a4_0><a6_0><b12_0>John Nash and Edward Blore<b12_0/><a6_0/><a4_0/>, who constructed three wings around a central courtyard. Buckingham Palace became the London residence of the British monarch on the accession of Queen Victoria in <a7_0>1837<a7_0/>.
